, as well as in the visual arts. Working in fields as disparate as traditional Chinese literature, religion, philosophy, history, medicine, and art, the contributors attempt to characterize one of the fundamental signifying practices in traditional Chinese cultural production. In the process, they not only reveal otherwise obscure patterns connecting longstanding social, political, aesthetic, and epistemological practices, but also contribute to ongoing discussions—well beyond the field of China studies—regarding the representation and communicability of knowledge, as well as the practices controlling its dissemination.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aHiding placeszChinaxHistory. 0aKnowledge, Theory of. 0aRhetoriczChinaxHistory. 0aSecrecyzChinaxHistory. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Art. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Literature. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aAsian Studies : Chinese Religion and Philosophy. 4aAsian Studies : Chinese Studies. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh1 aCai, Zong-Qi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuriyama, Shigehisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLi, Wai-Yee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNylan, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOwen, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPuett, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRobson, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchaberg, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTian, Xiaofei, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTseng, Lillian Lan-Ying, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/c